                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.512/687: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Cunningham</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1927-10-04T11:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 4, 1927—11 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received October 4—8:35 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Referring to paragraph 2 of my telegram of September 26, 4 p.m. and paragraph 4
                    of my September 20, 4 p.m., British consul general has now informed me that
                    American importers may obtain release of tobacco products, wines, and liquors
                    from British godowns upon deposit with me of only the treaty duty and wharfage
                    and conservancy dues and that they need not, as previously indicated, deposit
                    the two surtaxes. Repeated [to] the Legation.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Cunningham</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
